/* ============================================================================
   isc2 cc :: content/domain3.js - lazy-loaded reading module for ISC2 CC Domain 3 (deep).
   Populates ISC2CC.reading[3]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.ISC2CC = window.ISC2CC || {}; ISC2CC.reading = ISC2CC.reading || {};
ISC2CC.reading[3] = [];
ISC2CC.reading[3] = ISC2CC.reading[3] || [];
ISC2CC.reading[3].push(
  {
    heading: "Physical Facilities",
    body: "<p>Access control begins long before a user types a password. The first and most tangible layer of defense is the physical facility itself. <span class='keyterm'>Physical security</span> protects the people, hardware, software, and data of an organization from real-world threats such as theft, vandalism, sabotage, natural disaster, and unauthorized entry. The guiding philosophy is <span class='keyterm'>defense in depth</span> (also called layered defense): no single control is trusted to stop an intruder, so multiple independent controls are stacked so that defeating one still leaves several more to overcome. ISC2 frames this as concentric rings of protection that an attacker must penetrate in sequence &mdash; the perimeter, the building exterior, interior spaces, and finally the most sensitive assets such as the server room.</p>" +
      "<h3>The Layered Perimeter</h3>" +
      "<p>The outermost ring is the <span class='keyterm'>perimeter</span>, where the goal is to deter and delay. Fences, walls, gates, and natural barriers define where public space ends and controlled space begins. A standard chain-link fence three to four feet high is a casual deterrent; a fence six to seven feet high deters most determined intruders; eight feet or higher topped with three strands of barbed or razor wire is intended to stop a serious attacker. Beyond fencing, the perimeter may include <span class='keyterm'>bollards</span> (short, sturdy posts that stop vehicles from ramming a building), lighting, signage, and patrolling guards. Each element either deters an attacker from trying, delays them long enough for detection, or supports detection and response.</p>" +
      "<p>Moving inward, the building exterior is the next layer. Doors, windows, walls, and the roof must all be considered, because an attacker will look for the weakest entry point. Exterior doors should be solid-core or metal, hung in reinforced frames, and fitted with quality locks. Windows on lower floors may need bars, laminated glass, or alarm contacts. The principle is consistency: a vault-grade door beside an unlocked ground-floor window provides little real protection.</p>" +
      "<h3>Locks, Vestibules, and Turnstiles</h3>" +
      "<p>Locks are the most common physical control and range widely in sophistication. A <span class='keyterm'>key lock</span> is simple but suffers from key duplication and loss. A <span class='keyterm'>combination lock</span> removes physical keys but shares the weakness that combinations are easily shared and rarely changed. <span class='keyterm'>Electronic and smart locks</span> integrate with the logical access system, can be reprogrammed instantly when an employee leaves, and produce an audit log of every entry. Because they record who entered and when, electronic locks bridge physical and logical accountability.</p>" +
      "<p>To stop <span class='keyterm'>tailgating</span> or <span class='keyterm'>piggybacking</span> &mdash; an unauthorized person slipping in behind an authorized one &mdash; high-security facilities use an <span class='keyterm'>access control vestibule</span>, historically called a <span class='keyterm'>mantrap</span>. This is a small space bounded by two interlocking doors: the second door will not open until the first has closed and the individual has been authenticated, so only one person can pass at a time. <span class='keyterm'>Turnstiles</span> serve a similar function in higher-traffic areas, physically limiting passage to one person per authentication while being less restrictive than a full vestibule. Both controls directly counter the social-engineering tactic of following a legitimate badge-holder through a door.</p>" +
      "<h3>Badges, Proximity Cards, and the Data Center</h3>" +
      "<p>Identification and authentication at the physical layer are usually handled with <span class='keyterm'>badges</span> and cards. A photo badge supports visual identification by guards and coworkers. A <span class='keyterm'>proximity card</span> (prox card) contains an embedded chip and antenna that communicate wirelessly with a reader when held nearby, unlocking a door and logging the event without contact. Smart cards add a secure chip that can store credentials and perform cryptographic operations, often combined with a PIN to provide two factors. Badge systems should be centrally managed so that a lost or stolen card can be deactivated immediately, and so that each badge grants only the specific areas an individual needs.</p>" +
      "<p>The innermost ring &mdash; and the most sensitive &mdash; is typically the <span class='keyterm'>server room or data center</span>, which houses the systems and data the entire organization depends on. Access here should be tightly restricted to a short list of authorized personnel, enforced with the strongest controls available: badge plus PIN or biometric authentication, an access control vestibule, continuous video surveillance, and detailed logging. Environmental controls (cooling, fire suppression, power conditioning) protect availability, while strict entry controls protect confidentiality and integrity. Every layer reinforces the others so that compromising the perimeter does not compromise the crown jewels.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Example Controls</th><th>Primary Goal</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Perimeter</td><td>Fences, gates, bollards, lighting</td><td>Deter and delay</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Building exterior</td><td>Reinforced doors, window contacts, locks</td><td>Restrict entry points</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Interior</td><td>Vestibules, turnstiles, badge readers</td><td>Control and authenticate movement</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Sensitive assets</td><td>Server-room biometrics, CCTV, logging</td><td>Protect crown jewels</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Know that an <em>access control vestibule</em> (mantrap) defeats <em>tailgating/piggybacking</em> by allowing only one authenticated person through at a time. Turnstiles do the same in higher-traffic settings. If a question describes someone following an employee through a badge-controlled door, the control being defeated is anti-tailgating.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Designing for Security",
    body: "<p>Security is most effective and least expensive when it is designed into a facility from the start rather than bolted on afterward. The leading framework for this is <span class='keyterm'>Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design</span> (<span class='keyterm'>CPTED</span>). CPTED rests on the idea that the physical environment can be deliberately shaped to reduce the likelihood and fear of crime by influencing how people behave and how easily wrongdoing can be observed. Rather than relying solely on guards and gates, CPTED uses architecture, landscaping, and lighting to make legitimate use feel natural and illegitimate use feel exposed and unwelcome. It is built on three mutually reinforcing principles.</p>" +
      "<h3>The Three CPTED Principles</h3>" +
      "<p>The first principle is <span class='keyterm'>natural surveillance</span> &mdash; designing spaces so that people are naturally visible to others. When an area is open and well-lit, with clear sightlines and windows overlooking walkways and parking lots, potential intruders feel watched and are deterred, while legitimate occupants can spot suspicious activity. Practical measures include placing windows to overlook entrances, keeping shrubbery trimmed below window height, removing tall obstructions that create hiding spots, and using lighting to eliminate dark corners. The goal is to maximize the chance that an observer will notice wrongdoing.</p>" +
      "<p>The second principle is <span class='keyterm'>natural access control</span> &mdash; guiding people toward intended entrances and away from areas where they do not belong, using the layout itself rather than only locks and guards. Sidewalks, landscaping, decorative gates, and the placement of doors channel visitors to a single monitored reception point. A single, clearly marked main entrance funnels everyone past a check-in desk, while hedges or low walls discourage cutting across restricted areas. The environment quietly tells people where they may and may not go.</p>" +
      "<p>The third principle is <span class='keyterm'>territorial reinforcement</span> &mdash; using design to create a clear sense of ownership so that legitimate users feel a sense of control and intruders feel they are trespassing. Boundary markers such as changes in pavement, signage, fencing, landscaping, and well-maintained grounds communicate that the space is owned, cared for, and watched. A property that is clearly delineated and visibly maintained signals that someone is paying attention, which discourages casual intrusion and vandalism.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>CPTED Principle</th><th>Core Idea</th><th>Example Measures</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Natural surveillance</td><td>Make people and activity visible</td><td>Windows over entrances, lighting, trimmed shrubs</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Natural access control</td><td>Channel movement toward intended paths</td><td>Single main entrance, walkways, decorative gates</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Territorial reinforcement</td><td>Signal ownership and care</td><td>Signage, boundary markers, maintained grounds</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>Lighting, Fences, Bollards, and Signage</h3>" +
      "<p>Several concrete elements bring CPTED principles to life. <span class='keyterm'>Lighting</span> is one of the most cost-effective deterrents: well-lit entrances, walkways, and parking areas extend natural surveillance into the night and remove the concealment intruders rely on. Lighting should be even, avoid glare that blinds observers and cameras, and may be continuous, motion-triggered, or standby. Standards often call for entrances and critical areas to be illuminated to a minimum intensity so faces and activity remain identifiable on camera.</p>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Fences</span> mark territory and control access simultaneously, and their height and construction are matched to the threat &mdash; from a waist-high decorative fence that merely signals a boundary to a tall, anti-climb fence with razor wire that delays a determined intruder. <span class='keyterm'>Bollards</span> are short, strong posts &mdash; concrete, steel, or filled pipe &mdash; placed in front of building entrances, glass facades, and pedestrian areas to stop vehicle-ramming attacks while still allowing people to walk through. They protect against both accidental vehicle damage and deliberate vehicle-borne attacks.</p>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Signage</span> contributes to every CPTED principle at very low cost. Clear signs direct visitors to reception (access control), warn that an area is monitored or restricted (surveillance and deterrence), and assert ownership of the property (territorial reinforcement). A sign reading &quot;Authorized Personnel Only&quot; or &quot;This Area Is Under Video Surveillance&quot; both deters wrongdoing and removes any later claim of innocent confusion. Together, lighting, fences, bollards, and signage are the everyday building blocks that turn CPTED theory into a facility that is genuinely harder and less appealing to attack.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Scenario:</strong> A new office is being designed. The architect places the lobby with floor-to-ceiling windows facing the parking lot (natural surveillance), routes all visitor walkways to a single staffed front desk while landscaping blocks side paths (natural access control), and adds property-line signage, low decorative walls, and a well-kept lawn (territorial reinforcement). Bollards shield the glass lobby from vehicles and motion-activated lighting covers the lot after dark. No guard has been hired yet, but the design itself already deters and channels behavior &mdash; the essence of CPTED.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Memorize the three CPTED principles &mdash; natural surveillance, natural access control, and territorial reinforcement &mdash; and be able to match an example to the correct one. &quot;Windows overlooking the entrance&quot; is surveillance; &quot;single funneled entrance&quot; is access control; &quot;signage and boundary markers&quot; is territorial reinforcement.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Visitor Management",
    body: "<p>Not everyone inside a facility is an employee. Vendors, contractors, job candidates, auditors, delivery personnel, and guests all need temporary access, and each represents a potential risk to confidentiality, integrity, and availability. <span class='keyterm'>Visitor management</span> is the set of policies and procedures that controls who enters, where they may go, what they may see, and how their presence is recorded. A strong visitor program ensures that outsiders are identified, authorized, supervised, and accountable for the duration of their visit, closing a gap that attackers frequently exploit through social engineering.</p>" +
      "<h3>Sign-In, Badges, and Logs</h3>" +
      "<p>The cornerstone of visitor management is a formal <span class='keyterm'>sign-in process</span>. Upon arrival, a visitor presents government-issued identification, states the purpose of the visit, and names the employee they are meeting. This information is captured in a <span class='keyterm'>visitor log</span>, whether on paper or in an electronic kiosk. The log creates an audit trail showing exactly who was on the premises and when &mdash; invaluable for investigations, evacuation accountability, and demonstrating compliance to auditors. The host employee should be notified and confirm the visit before access is granted, preventing strangers from talking their way in.</p>" +
      "<p>Once verified, the visitor receives a <span class='keyterm'>visitor badge</span> that is visibly distinct from employee badges &mdash; often a different color, marked &quot;VISITOR,&quot; and frequently bearing an expiration. Some badges use ink that changes color or fades after a set number of hours, so a recycled or stolen badge becomes obviously invalid. The visitor badge does not grant the broad door access an employee badge does; it typically permits only common areas, with sensitive zones remaining off-limits. At the end of the visit, the visitor signs out and returns the badge, and the sign-out time is recorded to close the log entry.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Risk if Omitted</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Sign-in / ID check</td><td>Verify identity and purpose</td><td>Impostors enter unchecked</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Visitor log</td><td>Audit trail of who and when</td><td>No accountability after an incident</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Distinct visitor badge</td><td>Visual identification, limited access</td><td>Outsiders blend in with staff</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Escort</td><td>Continuous supervision</td><td>Unsupervised roaming and snooping</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>NDA</td><td>Legal protection of information</td><td>No recourse for disclosure</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>Escort Policy and NDAs</h3>" +
      "<p>For all but the most public areas, an <span class='keyterm'>escort policy</span> requires that a visitor be accompanied by an authorized employee at all times. The escort ensures the visitor goes only where the visit requires, does not view or photograph sensitive information, and cannot wander into restricted areas or plug into the network. Escorting is the single most effective control against a visitor who is actually a reconnaissance agent or thief, because it removes the unsupervised time an attacker needs. The host is responsible for the visitor from sign-in to sign-out and should never leave them alone in sensitive spaces.</p>" +
      "<p>Where a visitor may be exposed to confidential information &mdash; an auditor reviewing financial systems, a vendor integrating with a database, a candidate touring a lab &mdash; the organization commonly requires a <span class='keyterm'>non-disclosure agreement</span> (<span class='keyterm'>NDA</span>) before access is granted. The NDA is a legal contract binding the visitor to keep what they learn confidential and provides recourse if information is later disclosed. It complements the physical controls with a legal control, deterring misuse and clarifying obligations.</p>" +
      "<h3>Contractor and Vendor Access</h3>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Contractors</span> and vendors deserve special attention because they often need repeated or extended access, sometimes to sensitive systems, yet they are not full employees. Best practice treats long-term contractors much like employees for screening purposes &mdash; background checks, signed agreements, and individually issued, time-limited credentials &mdash; while still applying least privilege so they reach only the systems and areas their contract requires. Their access should have a defined expiration tied to the engagement, and it must be promptly revoked when the contract ends. Maintenance and delivery personnel who need only occasional entry should still sign in, wear visitor badges, and be escorted in sensitive areas.</p>" +
      "<p>A recurring danger is the contractor whose access outlives their need for it &mdash; a vendor account left active months after a project finished, or a service technician whose badge still opens the data-center door. Regular reviews of all non-employee accounts and badges, with automatic expiration as the default, keep this exposure in check. The overarching principle of visitor management is simple: every outsider is identified, authorized for the minimum necessary, supervised appropriately, recorded in a log, and de-provisioned the moment their legitimate need ends.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Scenario:</strong> An HVAC technician arrives unannounced claiming a service call. Following policy, reception checks ID, finds no scheduled work order, and phones facilities to confirm before issuing any badge. With no confirmed host or appointment, access is denied pending verification. This routine application of sign-in, host confirmation, and the no-confirmation-no-entry rule stops a classic social-engineering intrusion at the front desk.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> For ISC2 CC, the expected visitor controls are: sign in and verify ID, issue a distinct and time-limited visitor badge, maintain a log, escort the visitor in non-public areas, and require an NDA where confidential information may be exposed. Escorting is the key control that prevents unsupervised access.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Physical Security Personnel",
    body: "<p>Technology and architecture handle much of physical security, but people remain essential because only a human (or a human-supervised system) can exercise judgment, respond to the unexpected, and adapt to situations no automated rule anticipated. <span class='keyterm'>Physical security personnel</span> &mdash; guards, monitoring staff, and increasingly robotic and aerial assistants &mdash; provide the detection, deterrence, and response that complete a layered defense. Their presence alone deters many attackers, and their ability to make decisions on the spot is something locks and cameras cannot replicate.</p>" +
      "<h3>Security Guards and Their Duties</h3>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Security guards</span> are the most flexible physical control because they can reason about ambiguous situations. Typical duties include controlling and verifying entry at gates and lobbies, checking identification and badges, patrolling the perimeter and interior on foot or by vehicle, monitoring alarms and surveillance feeds, maintaining logs of events and visitors, and responding first to incidents such as intrusions, fires, or medical emergencies. A guard can notice that something is subtly wrong &mdash; a propped door, an unfamiliar face wearing a recycled badge, a person loitering near a loading dock &mdash; and investigate in a way no static control can. Guards may be in-house employees or provided by a contracted security firm, and they should be trained, vetted, and equipped with clear procedures.</p>" +
      "<p>The chief advantage of guards is discernment; their chief drawbacks are cost, fatigue, and the potential for human error or social-engineering manipulation. Because guards can be talked into bending rules, they must be backed by firm policies, supervision, and complementary controls. Guards also create accountability for their own actions through patrol logs and, where used, recorded check-in points along a route that prove the patrol actually occurred.</p>" +
      "<h3>Two-Person Integrity and CCTV Monitoring</h3>" +
      "<p>For especially sensitive operations, organizations apply <span class='keyterm'>two-person integrity</span> (also called two-person control or the two-person rule), which requires that two authorized individuals be present for a critical action. No single person can access the most sensitive asset or perform the most sensitive task alone, so collusion would be required to abuse the access. This both deters insider wrongdoing &mdash; since a would-be thief would need an accomplice &mdash; and protects the honest, because a second witness can vouch for what happened. It is common for vault access, handling of cryptographic keys, and entry to the most restricted areas.</p>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Closed-circuit television</span> (<span class='keyterm'>CCTV</span>) extends the reach of personnel by letting a small monitoring team watch many areas at once. Cameras serve as a deterrent (visible cameras discourage wrongdoing), a detective control (operators spot incidents in real time), and a forensic tool (recorded footage supports investigation and provides evidence). Effective CCTV pairs adequate camera coverage and image quality with attentive human monitoring or motion-triggered alerting, because hours of unwatched footage detect nothing in the moment. Recording retention policies determine how long footage is kept for later review.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Asset / Approach</th><th>Strength</th><th>Limitation</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Security guard</td><td>Judgment, flexible response</td><td>Cost, fatigue, manipulable</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Two-person integrity</td><td>Prevents solo insider abuse</td><td>Slower, requires staffing</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>CCTV monitoring</td><td>Wide coverage, evidence</td><td>Needs attentive watcher</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Robots / drones</td><td>Tireless, dull/dangerous tasks</td><td>Limited judgment, cost</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>Robots, Drones, and Response Procedures</h3>" +
      "<p>Automation increasingly supplements human personnel. <span class='keyterm'>Security robots</span> can patrol predictable routes, stream video, read license plates, detect heat or motion, and flag anomalies for human review, performing the dull, repetitive watching that fatigues people. <span class='keyterm'>Drones</span> (unmanned aerial vehicles) extend surveillance over large or hard-to-reach areas such as expansive perimeters, rooftops, and storage yards, providing rapid aerial assessment during an incident. These tools are tireless and consistent but lack genuine judgment, so they augment rather than replace trained personnel, who remain in the loop to interpret and act on what the machines report.</p>" +
      "<p>Underpinning all of this are clear <span class='keyterm'>response procedures</span>. Personnel must know exactly what to do when an alarm sounds, an intruder is detected, a fire breaks out, or a medical emergency occurs &mdash; whom to notify, how to escalate to law enforcement or emergency services, how to safely evacuate occupants, and how to preserve evidence afterward. Documented, rehearsed procedures turn a chaotic event into an orderly response. The combination of trained guards, the two-person rule for critical access, attentive CCTV monitoring, robotic and aerial augmentation, and well-practiced response procedures gives the physical layer the human judgment and reach that technology alone cannot provide.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Distinguish <em>two-person integrity</em> (two people must be present for a sensitive action, preventing solo abuse) from <em>separation of duties</em> (a process is split so no one person controls it end to end). Both reduce insider risk, but two-person integrity is about simultaneous presence, while separation of duties is about dividing the steps of a task.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Authorization and the Principle of Least Privilege",
    body: "<p>Once a subject has been identified and authenticated, the system must decide what that subject is permitted to do. This decision is <span class='keyterm'>authorization</span>: granting or denying specific rights and permissions to a verified identity. Authorization always follows authentication &mdash; proving who you are comes before determining what you may access &mdash; and it is governed by one of the most important ideas in all of security: the <span class='keyterm'>principle of least privilege</span>. Least privilege holds that every subject (user, process, or system) should be granted only the minimum access required to perform its legitimate function, and no more. By keeping permissions tight, an organization limits the damage that any single account can do, whether the account is misused by a malicious insider, hijacked by an attacker, or simply makes an honest mistake.</p>" +
      "<h3>Need-to-Know and Least Privilege</h3>" +
      "<p>Closely related is the concept of <span class='keyterm'>need-to-know</span>, which restricts access to information specifically to those whose duties require it, even among people who hold the appropriate clearance level. Clearance establishes the maximum sensitivity a person may handle; need-to-know narrows that to the particular items they actually need for their job. An analyst cleared for confidential data still should not see a confidential file about a project they are not assigned to. Least privilege is the broader principle covering all access rights (read, write, execute, delete, configure), while need-to-know is its application to knowledge of information. Together they ensure that access is justified by genuine business need rather than convenience or status.</p>" +
      "<p>Applying least privilege well requires deliberate effort, because the path of least resistance is to over-grant. Administrators are tempted to copy an existing user's permissions, add someone to a broad group, or grant administrator rights to avoid future tickets. Each shortcut quietly expands the attack surface. The disciplined alternative is to grant access based on documented role requirements, review it regularly, and remove anything no longer needed.</p>" +
      "<h3>Separation of Duties and Privilege Creep</h3>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Separation of duties</span> (also called segregation of duties) divides a sensitive process into parts so that no single individual controls it from start to finish. The classic example is requiring one person to request a payment and a different person to approve it, so that committing fraud would require collusion between two people. Separation of duties reduces both the opportunity and the temptation for abuse, and it embodies least privilege at the process level: no one person holds all the permissions needed to complete a high-risk task alone.</p>" +
      "<p>The natural enemy of least privilege is <span class='keyterm'>privilege creep</span> (also called permission or access creep). As employees change roles, join new projects, or cover for absent colleagues, they accumulate access rights &mdash; but those rights are rarely removed when no longer needed. Over months and years, a long-tenured employee can amass far more access than their current job requires, violating least privilege and creating a high-value target. The remedy is the periodic <span class='keyterm'>access review</span> (recertification), in which managers re-validate each person's access and revoke whatever is unnecessary, and prompt updates whenever someone changes roles.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>What It Restricts</th><th>Goal</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Least privilege</td><td>All access rights to the minimum</td><td>Limit damage from any account</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Need-to-know</td><td>Access to information specifically</td><td>Restrict knowledge to those who require it</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Separation of duties</td><td>One person controlling a whole process</td><td>Prevent solo fraud; require collusion</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Just-in-time access</td><td>Standing elevated privileges</td><td>Grant power only when and as long as needed</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>Just-in-Time Access</h3>" +
      "<p>A modern refinement of least privilege is <span class='keyterm'>just-in-time</span> (JIT) access, which grants elevated privileges only at the moment they are needed and automatically revokes them afterward. Instead of an administrator holding standing privileged access around the clock &mdash; a permanent, attractive target &mdash; the person requests elevation when a specific task arises, the access is granted for a limited window (often with approval and logging), and it expires automatically when the task or time window ends. JIT shrinks the time during which powerful permissions exist, dramatically reducing the opportunity for those credentials to be abused or stolen. It is the temporal expression of least privilege: minimum access, for the minimum time.</p>" +
      "<p>Taken together, these concepts make authorization a discipline rather than a default. Access is granted narrowly, justified by need, divided across people for sensitive tasks, reviewed to prevent creep, and elevated only momentarily when extra power is genuinely required. Each idea independently shrinks the blast radius of a compromised or misused account, and together they form the backbone of sound access control.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Least-privilege scenario:</strong> A help-desk technician named Dana moves to the finance team. Her old role required resetting passwords and unlocking accounts; her new role requires read access to the accounts-payable system. Under least privilege, IT removes her help-desk administrative rights and grants only the specific finance read access her new duties require &mdash; not a copy of a senior accountant's full permissions. When Dana later needs to run a one-time year-end export requiring elevated rights, she is granted that power through just-in-time access for two hours, after which it expires automatically. No standing excess privilege ever accumulates.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Least privilege = minimum access to do the job. Need-to-know = access to specific information only. Separation of duties = split a task so no one controls it alone. Privilege creep is the gradual accumulation of unneeded rights, fixed by regular access reviews. Expect questions that ask you to match the scenario to the correct principle.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Account Types",
    body: "<p>Access control is enforced through <span class='keyterm'>accounts</span> &mdash; the digital identities that represent users and processes on a system. Not all accounts are equal: they differ in their purpose, the level of privilege they carry, and the risks they introduce. Understanding the major <span class='keyterm'>account types</span> and applying the right controls to each is fundamental to authorization, because the riskiest breaches often trace back to a powerful or poorly managed account. Classifying accounts also clarifies how the principle of least privilege should be applied to each.</p>" +
      "<h3>The Major Account Types</h3>" +
      "<p>A <span class='keyterm'>standard user account</span> represents an ordinary individual and carries only the everyday permissions needed for that person's job. It is the default and most common account type, and it should be the type used for routine work even by administrators, who switch to a privileged account only when elevated action is required. A <span class='keyterm'>privileged or administrative account</span> holds elevated rights &mdash; installing software, changing configurations, managing other accounts, accessing sensitive data &mdash; and is therefore the highest-value target in the environment. Compromise of an administrative account can mean compromise of the entire system, so these accounts demand the strongest protections: multi-factor authentication, strict least privilege, close monitoring, and ideally just-in-time elevation rather than standing access.</p>" +
      "<p>A <span class='keyterm'>service account</span> is used by an application, process, or system rather than a human &mdash; for example, the account a web application uses to reach its database. Service accounts often run continuously, may hold significant privileges, and are easy to forget, which makes them dangerous if over-privileged or given weak, never-changed passwords. They should be granted least privilege, have strong and rotated credentials, be barred from interactive login, and be inventoried so none is overlooked. A <span class='keyterm'>guest account</span> provides limited, temporary access for occasional or anonymous users; it carries minimal privileges and should be disabled when not in active use, since enabled-by-default guest accounts are a classic entry point for attackers.</p>" +
      "<p>A <span class='keyterm'>shared or generic account</span> is used by more than one person &mdash; a single login that several staff use. Shared accounts are strongly discouraged because they destroy <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span>: when multiple people use one identity, the audit log cannot tie an action to an individual, so non-repudiation is lost. Where a shared account is truly unavoidable, its use must be tightly controlled, its password closely managed and frequently changed, and compensating logging applied. Wherever possible, each person should have a unique account.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Account Type</th><th>Primary Risk</th><th>Key Control</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>Standard user</td><td>Phishing, credential theft</td><td>Least privilege, MFA, training</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Privileged / admin</td><td>Total system compromise</td><td>MFA, JIT elevation, monitoring</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Service</td><td>Over-privilege, stale credentials</td><td>Least privilege, rotated secrets, no interactive login</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Guest</td><td>Unmonitored entry point</td><td>Disable when unused, minimal rights</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Shared / generic</td><td>Loss of accountability</td><td>Avoid; if required, log and manage tightly</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>The Account Lifecycle: Provisioning and Deprovisioning</h3>" +
      "<p>Every account has a lifecycle that must be managed deliberately. <span class='keyterm'>Provisioning</span> is the creation and authorization of an account when a person joins or changes roles. Done well, provisioning follows least privilege from the outset: the account is granted exactly the access the role requires, based on documented role definitions rather than copying someone else's permissions. Tying provisioning to the HR onboarding process ensures accounts are created accurately and approved by the right authority.</p>" +
      "<p>Throughout the account's life, periodic <span class='keyterm'>access reviews</span> revalidate that its permissions still match the holder's duties, catching the privilege creep that accumulates as roles change. The most critical and most frequently neglected stage is <span class='keyterm'>deprovisioning</span> &mdash; promptly disabling or removing access when a person leaves the organization or no longer needs it. An <span class='keyterm'>orphaned account</span> left active after an employee departs is a serious vulnerability: it offers an attacker (or a disgruntled former employee) a working credential with no one watching it. Deprovisioning should be immediate upon termination, ideally automated and triggered by the HR system, so the window of exposure is as short as possible.</p>" +
      "<p>Strong account management therefore spans the whole lifecycle: provision narrowly, review regularly, and deprovision promptly. Applying these stages consistently across every account type &mdash; and being especially vigilant with privileged, service, and shared accounts &mdash; is one of the highest-impact things an organization can do to control access.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Scenario:</strong> An employee is terminated on Friday afternoon. Because deprovisioning is integrated with HR, the moment the termination is recorded, the employee's standard account is disabled, their badge is deactivated, and their membership in privileged groups is removed automatically. A weekly access review separately flags a service account that hadn't been used in 90 days; investigation shows it belonged to a retired application, and it is disabled. Both actions close orphaned-credential gaps before they can be exploited.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Shared/generic accounts are discouraged because they break accountability and non-repudiation &mdash; the log cannot prove which individual acted. Guest accounts should be disabled when not in use. Privileged accounts get the strongest controls. Prompt deprovisioning prevents orphaned accounts.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Access Control Models",
    body: "<p>An <span class='keyterm'>access control model</span> is the underlying logic an organization uses to decide which subjects may access which objects and in what way. The model determines who has the authority to set permissions, how those permissions are expressed, and how access decisions are made when a subject requests an object. ISC2 CC focuses on several primary models &mdash; <span class='keyterm'>discretionary</span>, <span class='keyterm'>mandatory</span>, <span class='keyterm'>role-based</span>, <span class='keyterm'>attribute-based</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>rule-based</span> access control &mdash; each striking a different balance between flexibility, security, and administrative effort. Choosing a model is choosing where the power to grant access lives and how rigid or adaptable the rules are.</p>" +
      "<h3>Discretionary and Mandatory Access Control</h3>" +
      "<p>In <span class='keyterm'>Discretionary Access Control</span> (<span class='keyterm'>DAC</span>), the owner of an object decides who may access it and at their own discretion grants or revokes permissions. This is the model behind everyday file systems: the person who creates a document can share it, change its permissions, or pass ownership along. DAC is flexible and intuitive, which is why it is so common, but that same flexibility is its weakness &mdash; owners may grant access too freely, permissions sprawl, and a compromised owner account can hand out broad access. Control is decentralized to individual owners rather than enforced centrally.</p>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Mandatory Access Control</span> (<span class='keyterm'>MAC</span>) is the opposite extreme. Access is dictated by the system according to security <span class='keyterm'>labels</span> and clearances set by a central authority, and ordinary users cannot change permissions &mdash; not even the owner of a file. Every object carries a classification (for example, Confidential, Secret, Top Secret) and every subject carries a clearance; the system permits access only when the subject's clearance and need-to-know satisfy the object's label. MAC is the most rigid and most secure model, which is why it dominates military, government, and other high-security environments, but its inflexibility and administrative overhead make it impractical for typical commercial use.</p>" +
      "<h3>Role-Based, Attribute-Based, and Rule-Based</h3>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Role-Based Access Control</span> (<span class='keyterm'>RBAC</span>) grants permissions to <span class='keyterm'>roles</span> rather than to individuals, and users receive access by being assigned to a role that matches their job function. An administrator defines a &quot;Nurse&quot; role or an &quot;Accounts-Payable Clerk&quot; role with a set of permissions, and anyone placed in that role inherits exactly those permissions. RBAC scales beautifully in organizations with well-defined job functions: onboarding becomes assigning a role, role changes are clean, and least privilege is easier to maintain because permissions track job duties. It is the dominant model in modern enterprises.</p>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Attribute-Based Access Control</span> (<span class='keyterm'>ABAC</span>) makes decisions by evaluating <span class='keyterm'>attributes</span> of the subject, the object, the action, and the environment against policies. Attributes might include the user's department, the data's classification, the time of day, the device, or the network location. ABAC is the most granular and dynamic model &mdash; for example, &quot;permit if the user is in Finance, on a managed device, during business hours&quot; &mdash; allowing fine-grained, context-aware decisions that the other models cannot easily express, at the cost of greater complexity to design and manage. <span class='keyterm'>Rule-Based Access Control</span> applies global rules or conditions, set by an administrator, that govern access regardless of identity &mdash; a firewall that allows or blocks traffic by rule, or a system that denies all logins outside business hours, is rule-based. The rules apply uniformly to everyone rather than being tied to a particular user or owner.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Who Sets Permissions</th><th>Basis of Decision</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>DAC</td><td>The object's owner</td><td>Owner's discretion</td><td>Sharing a file you created</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>MAC</td><td>Central authority (system)</td><td>Labels and clearances</td><td>Top Secret military document</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>RBAC</td><td>Administrator, via roles</td><td>User's job role</td><td>&quot;Nurse&quot; role grants chart access</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>ABAC</td><td>Administrator, via policy</td><td>Attributes and context</td><td>Allow if Finance + managed device + business hours</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Rule-based</td><td>Administrator, via rules</td><td>Global conditions for all</td><td>Firewall rule; no logins after hours</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<p>The models are not mutually exclusive; real systems often combine them. A network might use rule-based filtering at the firewall, RBAC for application permissions, and DAC for individual file sharing, all at once. The art of access control is matching the model to the asset: rigid MAC for the most sensitive classified data, scalable RBAC for enterprise applications, flexible DAC for collaborative documents, and dynamic ABAC where context must drive the decision.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Scenario:</strong> A hospital implements RBAC: assigning the &quot;Nurse&quot; role grants chart-read access to all nurses without touching individual permissions. For its classified research division it layers MAC, so files labeled Secret are accessible only to cleared staff and no owner can override the system. Patients sharing their own uploaded documents through the portal use DAC. The firewall protecting the data center runs rule-based filtering that blocks all external traffic to clinical systems. One environment, four models, each chosen to fit the asset.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Anchor each model to who sets permissions: DAC = the owner decides; MAC = the system enforces labels/clearances and users cannot change them; RBAC = access by job role; ABAC = access by attributes/context; rule-based = global rules applied to everyone. MAC is the most secure and rigid; RBAC is the most common in enterprises; DAC is the most flexible.</div>"
  },
  {
    heading: "Logical Access Controls and Enforcing Non-repudiation",
    body: "<p>Where physical controls protect facilities, <span class='keyterm'>logical access controls</span> (also called technical controls) protect systems, applications, and data through software and hardware mechanisms rather than walls and locks. Passwords, encryption, access control lists, and audit logs are all logical controls. Their purpose is to enforce the authorization decisions discussed earlier &mdash; ensuring that each authenticated subject can reach only the objects and perform only the actions they are permitted &mdash; and, critically, to create a record that ties actions to identities. That linkage is the foundation of accountability and <span class='keyterm'>non-repudiation</span>.</p>" +
      "<h3>Unique IDs, ACLs, and Capabilities</h3>" +
      "<p>The cornerstone of logical access control is the <span class='keyterm'>unique identifier</span>. Every user and process must have its own distinct, non-shared account so that every action can be attributed to exactly one identity. Unique IDs are what make accountability possible; the moment an identity is shared, the system can no longer prove who did what. This is precisely why shared and generic accounts are discouraged &mdash; they sever the link between an action and an individual.</p>" +
      "<p>Two complementary structures express who may access what. An <span class='keyterm'>access control list</span> (<span class='keyterm'>ACL</span>) is attached to an object and lists the subjects permitted to access it and what each may do &mdash; the object's point of view: &quot;this file may be read by Alice and edited by Bob.&quot; A <span class='keyterm'>capability</span> takes the subject's point of view: it is a token or list associated with a subject that enumerates the objects that subject may access &mdash; &quot;Alice may read these files and run these programs.&quot; ACLs are organized around objects and capabilities around subjects, and most systems lean on ACLs, but both are mechanisms for recording and enforcing permissions at a fine granularity.</p>" +
      "<table><thead><tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>Perspective</th><th>It Answers</th></tr></thead><tbody>" +
      "<tr><td>ACL</td><td>Object-centric</td><td>Who may access this object?</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Capability</td><td>Subject-centric</td><td>What may this subject access?</td></tr>" +
      "<tr><td>Audit trail</td><td>Event-centric</td><td>Who did what, and when?</td></tr>" +
      "</tbody></table>" +
      "<h3>Audit Trails, Accountability, and AAA</h3>" +
      "<p>An <span class='keyterm'>audit trail</span> (or audit log) is a chronological record of system events &mdash; logins, file accesses, configuration changes, failed attempts &mdash; each stamped with the identity responsible, the action taken, and the time it occurred. Audit trails turn raw activity into <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span>: the assurance that every action can be traced to the individual who performed it. Accountability is impossible without two prerequisites &mdash; unique identification (so there is a specific identity to hold responsible) and reliable logging (so there is a record of what that identity did). Logs must themselves be protected from tampering, because an audit trail that an attacker can edit proves nothing.</p>" +
      "<p>These ideas fit into the framework of <span class='keyterm'>AAA</span> &mdash; <span class='keyterm'>Authentication</span>, <span class='keyterm'>Authorization</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>Accounting</span>. Authentication verifies who a subject is; authorization determines what that subject may do; and accounting records what the subject actually did. Logical access controls implement all three: credentials and identity systems handle authentication, ACLs and access models handle authorization, and audit logging handles accounting. The accounting leg is the one that produces the evidence trail, and it is essential to the final concept of this domain.</p>" +
      "<h3>Enforcing Non-repudiation Through Logging</h3>" +
      "<p><span class='keyterm'>Non-repudiation</span> is the assurance that a subject cannot credibly deny having performed an action &mdash; they cannot say &quot;it wasn't me.&quot; It is the property that makes accountability stick, because it removes the defense of denial. Logging is one of the principal ways non-repudiation is enforced: when each action is recorded against a unique identity in a tamper-resistant audit trail, the record itself contradicts any later denial. If the log shows that the user account belonging to one specific person, authenticated with their own credentials, deleted a file at a specific time, that person cannot convincingly claim it was someone else.</p>" +
      "<p>Several conditions must hold for logging to enforce non-repudiation effectively. Each subject must have a unique, non-shared identity, so the action maps to exactly one person; the action must be reliably captured the moment it occurs; the logs must be protected from alteration or deletion, often by writing them to a separate, secured system; and the records must be retained long enough to support investigation. Where stronger assurance is required, cryptographic measures such as digital signatures bind an action irrefutably to a private key held by one identity, providing non-repudiation that even a privileged insider cannot easily forge. The throughline of this domain is now complete: identify uniquely, authenticate, authorize with least privilege, and then account for every action through protected logs &mdash; so that access is both controlled and provably attributable.</p>" +
      "<div class='callout scenario'><strong>Scenario:</strong> A sensitive customer record is altered. Because every employee has a unique login, the application required authentication, and all changes are written to a tamper-resistant audit log on a separate server, the investigation pinpoints the exact account, the change made, and the timestamp. The employee cannot repudiate the action &mdash; the protected log, tied to their unique identity, is the evidence. Had a shared account been used, no individual could have been held accountable.</div>" +
      "<div class='callout exam'><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Non-repudiation depends on two things: unique identification and protected logging (audit trails). Shared accounts destroy non-repudiation. In AAA, <em>accounting</em> is the logging leg that records what a user did and underpins both accountability and non-repudiation. Digital signatures provide the strongest form of non-repudiation.</div>"
  }
);

